---

## The Problem

Every document type has its own tool.

<cards cols="3">
  <card title="LaTeX" variant="outline">
  Beautiful math. Terrible learning curve. 200 lines to change a margin.
  </card>
  <card title="Markdown" variant="outline">
  Simple prose. Can't do math. Can't do diagrams. No layout primitives.
  </card>
  <card title="Notion / Confluence" variant="outline">
  Great for notes. No math. No real code. Proprietary. Export is broken.
  </card>
</cards>

<warning>
You end up maintaining **four different tools** for four document types —
all with different syntax, different export formats, and different workflows.
</warning>

---

## The Solution

<hero title="One Syntax"
      subtitle="Markdown prose + HTML-style tags for everything else."
      align="left">
</hero>

**Rule 1** — Prose, headings, lists, tables → **Markdown**

**Rule 2** — Math, diagrams, charts, layouts → **`<Tag attr="value">`**

That's the entire language spec.

---

## Syntax at a Glance

<tabs>
  <tab title="Math">

```zolto
Inline: <m>E = mc^2</m>

Block:
<math>
\oint_C \mathbf{B} \cdot d\mathbf{l}
  = \mu_0 \left( I + \varepsilon_0 \frac{d\Phi_E}{dt} \right)
</math>
```

  </tab>
  <tab title="Diagrams">

```zolto
<diagram type="sequence" title="Request lifecycle">
Browser --> CDN: GET /page
CDN --> Origin: Cache MISS
Origin --> DB: SELECT
DB --> Origin: rows
Origin --> CDN: 200 + Cache-Control
CDN --> Browser: 200 (cached)
</diagram>
```

  </tab>
  <tab title="Components">

```zolto
<component name="Feature" props="icon, title">
<card variant="ghost">
  <header>{icon} {title}</header>
  <body><slot/></body>
</card>
</component>

<Feature icon="⚡" title="Fast">
Parses 10,000 lines in under 40 ms.
</Feature>
```

  </tab>
</tabs>

---

## Architecture

<diagram type="flowchart">
Input .zl -->
  Tokenizer -->
  Lexer -->
  Parser -->
  Transformer -->
  Renderer -->
  HTML Output

Transformer --> MathRenderer --> KaTeX SVG
Transformer --> DiagramRenderer --> SVG
Transformer --> ComponentRuntime --> expanded AST
</diagram>

